            If there is any art form
that cannot pay its own way, it is opera. Since <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">the early 18</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">th</ENAMEX>
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">century</ENAMEX>, when <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">George Friedrich Handel</ENAMEX> struggled to keep a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORG_DESC">company</ENAMEX> going in
<ENAMEX TYPE="GPE">London</ENAMEX>, opera has been sustainable only with the help of subsidies--whether
from aristocrats, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORG_DESC">governments</ENAMEX>, or corporate <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">benefactors</ENAMEX>. Even with tickets
priced <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">up to $125</NUMEX> and higher at the best <ENAMEX TYPE="ORG_DESC">houses</ENAMEX> in the <ENAMEX TYPE="GPE">United States</ENAMEX>, box
